Date : 05/2025

## üõ†Ô∏è How it work ?
The EPI-WEATHER project measures temperature and humidity using a DHT11 sensor connected to an Arduino Uno board. The collected data is displayed in real-time on an OLED SSD1306 screen via I2C. At the same time, this data is sent to a web server installed on a Raspberry Pi 4, allowing the data to be viewed remotely on a browser.

## üß∞ Materials required

| Component            | Reference               |
| -------------------- | ----------------------- |
| Microcontroller      | Arduino Uno R3          |
| Temp/Humidity Sensor | DHT11                   |
| I2C OLED Display     | SSD1306 (128x64)        |
| Jumper Wires         | Male-to-Female (M/F)    |
| Computer             | With USB port           |
| Local WiFi Network   | Box, router, or hotspot |
| (Optional) Server    | Raspberry Pi 4          |

## üîå Wiring Diagram

| OLED Pin    | Arduino Uno Pin  |
| ------------|------------------|
| VCC         | 5V               |
| GND         | GND              |
| SDA         | A4               |
| SCL         | A5               |


| Temp/Humidity Sensor  | Arduino Uno Pin  |
| ----------------------|------------------|
| GND                   | GND              |
| VCC                   | 3.5V             |
| DATA                  | Pin2             |


## üíª Framework Used

The EPI-WEATHER project is developed using PlatformIO within the Visual Studio Code IDE.